Jan 28 2008 	Good for business	I concur with most of the other reviewers, this is a fine business-oriented hotel with excellent large rooms many facing the creek. I had an almost-corner with lots of space, a pleasant view and superb all-granite bathroom with separate two-person shower, lovely deep granite-surrounded bath (with obligatory scented oil candle burner at turndown) and was completely comfortable.The staff, particularly the young ladies who run the Executive Lounge can't do enough for you, and everyone from the room boys to the waiters ran rings round each other to be helpful.Breakfast is indeed a bit of an oddity, with a generous cold buffet but call-order cooking for the hot items, some of which suffer in translation - but any minor errors were cheerfully rectified.The small niggles are the unheated rooftop pool, very chilly in the current cold snap but probably cool all year round, and the rather small gym. Also you wouldn't really want to holiday here because this Hilton is not near the beach nor the popular shopping malls - this may be why I like its comparatively quiet and chav-free atmosphere.I ate one night at &quot;Verre&quot;, the Gordon Ramsay branded a la carte restaurant and I have to say it was one of the most irritating and boring evenings I've ever had in a restaurant.Firstly, it's quite uncomortable - the tables are too close together and there's no view nor interest in the decor, not even great flowers or arrays of wine bottles, it's a pretty bland dull room. The French-ified manager is so far up himself even Gordon would have a problem to slap some customer service out of him, and the mostly Indian waiters whilst charming have been drilled into formulaic, scripted service which saps the life out of the whole experience, and leaves you feeling exhausted and processed.The presentation of food is fawning and beyond pretentious. &quot;May I present your pre-starter starter&quot;, &quot;Did you enjoy your amuses-bouches&quot;, indicated the number and incidence of the additional courses which mean you don't really need to order more than two or three from the menu because you could almost make your meal off the amuses-bouches of pate, pastry straws and vegetable pure, the pre-starter complimentary soup, the pre-dessert dessert (a vile concoction of fruit and shaving foam which reminded me of the Lyons Maid &quot;peach parfait&quot; plastic cone ice creams we had at Saturday morning cinema when I was about ten), the petits fours and the complimentary chocolates.Everything has four too many ingredients - and the humourless management won't permit any variation to the order, portion control is clearly king ... when I suggested I might prefer more scallop and less pork belly in my oddly combined starter, the manager said &quot;it's three pieces scallop and two of pork, take it or leave it&quot; ... and I wish I'd left it. The scallops were OK, but the caramelised pork belly roundels were greasy and nasty, and the pan-fried watermelon 'earplugs' (because that's what they looked like) that accompanied it were downright laughable. I mean, who fries watermelon?Fillet of beef was a small portion and a nice cut, and the menu listed the many accompaniments including caramelised salsify, celeriac puree, potatoes and madeira jus. When it arrived in a wobbling tower with a fried quail egg slimily perched on the top, I could cheerfully have thrown it across the room. Egg is such a popular allergy, why not mention its presence on the menu?By the time I'd worked my way through the inter-courses to the chocolate and caramel semifreddo, I was bored beyond my capacity to enjoy the experience and just wanted to get out of the place, and breathe.My fellow diners were mostly middle-aged British couples too awed by Ramsay's TV fame and their opportunity to worship at the shrine to realise that this was over-complicated food with pompous service which feels outdated and claustrophobic.My summary for the Hilton? Sleep in, eat out!	
Jan 15 2008 	Class and elegance	We stayed in the Hilton Dubai Creek in mid Dec 2007 and early Jan 2008, and thoroughly loved both visits. In a city renowned for its glitz and OTT &quot;glam&quot;, the Hilton Dubai Creek seems to be in its own category of pure class and elegance. The rooms are beautifully finished and furnished. One detail that I found particularly great was that I could not hear the noise from people in the hallway. This is probably due to the boutique size of the property, so that there aren't that many people walking past the rooms; the fact that the doors are very heavy and solid; and that the beds are placed in a position that minimises exposure to hallway noise. In January, we flew from New York to the Emirates. It was a horrific flight (numerous families each with 4-6 ill-mannered and LOUD children) that made me homicidal and suicidal. After a spa bath in the beautifully appointed bathroom overlooking Dubai Creek, I lay in the bed with exceptionally soft sheets, a soft down comforter, a soft down pillow; luxuriating in this slice of heaven. It was just what I needed. The staff are friendly, responsive and professional I found all of them to be extremely helpful. e.g. I asked the operator for the phone number of Etihad Airways. She gave me two numbers. Neither worked and when I rang her back for further assistance, she was apologetic and immediately offered to find a couple of more numbers and told me that if these still did not work, to call her back. One of the four finally did work, but I was really impressed with her tenacity and willingness to make sure that I got what I needed. In a city filled with hotels and other establishments screaming louder and louder to be noticed, the Hilton Dubai Creek is the picture of refined grace.	
Jan 3 2008 	over-rated	I think the main problem at this hotel is the lack of training for staff.I stayed for 2 nights in late December in Executive room. Despite being asked several times about my request for a non-smoking room, I was assigned a smoking room in a &quot;non-smoking configuration&quot;. Given I was recovering from bronchitis, I was not impressed and asked to be assigned another room. There was apparently almost full occupancy - I was offered a *downgrade*, and a similar, smoking room! This was also unacceptable, so I stayed where I was.The exec rooms are OK - fantastic view - but configured rather strangely, lots of empty space, but so that the desk is jammed into a small space in one corner of the room - not great for working at. There was mineral water, but no complimentary fruit. The exec. lounge is ludicrously small for the number of executive rooms (over 3 floors!) in the hotel.I expect that in a 5* international hotel, the staff on the front desk will speak english. As a native english speaker, I experienced real problems a few times in making myself understood to the front desk staff. This is also unacceptable. While the staff were friendly, some clearly need more training in communicating in english.Breakfast in the Glasshouse was a disappointment. The hot dishes need to be ordered, which is fine. However, after ordering the arabic breakfast, I received about half of the items that were advertised in the menu, and no hot dish! I was only told that the hot dish was 'off' by the waitress after she brought my order to the table, not beforehand. Again, staff training seemed to be an issue.The amenities at this hotel are also lacking for a 5* international hotel. The pool has an undeniably beautiful view, but there are no other facilities such as a steam room or a sauna. The gym is one of the smallest I've seen for this standard of hotel.In summary, I think you can do much better for a 5* hotel. While the location is good, this hotel seems content to rest on its laurels.	
