Jan 2 2007 	It's OK but we wouldn't go back	We booked here for 6 nights Dec 25 - Jan 31.We booked and paid for an executive room.I'm HH Gold and got no upgrade or benefits because of this.On the plus side we arrived at the hotel (via the private transfer in a nice car) at 8am, by 9am they had a room ready for us so I was pleased about that, obviously this is just down to chance though.The room itself was OK, no wow factor for us despite the floor to ceiling windows and a nice bathroom, it just wasn't all that special in our opinion. The beds were comfy though, our view was part creek and mostly of the big building next to the hotel!Now, onto the executive lounge - IT IS DREADFULL. It too small for one thing. They have a coffee machine so you can help yourself to that all day. Soft drinks are supposed to be available all day, they are but you have to either ask for one or wait to be asked. The problem is there was often just one member of staff in there and they were mostly busy at the desk so you had to wait ages for a simple glass of water. Most lounges I've been in have soft drinks and water available for you to help yourself too, they could have some small fridges under the counters on the side, there is room.Happy hour was OK but if you wanted beer or wine, you had to ask for it or wait to be asked, it was a nightmare when it was busy as you can imagine. They did leave spirits out and a few (and I mean very few) cans of soft drinks out at happy hour.The food offerings we're very poor too, the room was too warm and they would have salmon, mayo (In sandwiches) etc just sat out in it for hours, you'd have to be desperate to eat there!Being in an exec room we should've had fruit delivered daily but this only happened after we complained about not getting it for two days.We ate at the Glasshouse on Christmas Day, this was really nice and a reasonable price too. We had breakfast included but only went 4 days. Breakfast was just OK, sure it was a buffett but not too exciting, plus I witnessed too many people just picking things up and putting them down again or not using a cloth to hold the breads when cutting them. You could order hot stuff from the menu but the portions were small, but well presented and always very greasy if ordering bacon or omlettes or anything similar.I can't complain about the location as we knew exactly where it was and what to expect. It was handy for us to go off and watch football in the Chelsea Arms pub in the Sheraton which was just a couple of minutes walk away.The fitness centre is tiny, two treadmills, one bike, one recline bike, one cross trainer and a knackered rower plus 4 fixed weight machines and some free weights. It was all very cramped and again, it was too hot to work out in properly.We had no trouble with the staff and we never had problems getting a taxi either. All the staff were very friendly.We popped up to the pool area, it looked nice but was always busy as it's very small, we never intended on sunbathing as we never thought it was warm enough, especially as it was always breezy up there.Overall I can only give it 3 out of 5 as we were just dissapointed with it all, it just did not live up to the tripadvisor hype for us.	
Dec 28 2006 	The mediocre Dubai Hilton	Overall I have given the Hilton a score of 3 out of 5 - the reason for this is the quality of the hotel against the other 2 hotels we stayed in during our holiday - The Jumerah Beach Hotel and the Fairmont that we leagues apart.I can see why travellers say that the Hilton Dubai Creek is the best city (Deira hotel) - quite simply it probably is - although though there is little real competition along the Creek. I visited Dubai 10 years ago and the creek was a happening place - then we stayed at the old Intercontinenal - however nowadays all the action is either at the Marina, Jumerah Beach or Sheik Zayed Road. The best thing about the Creek is the fact that it is near the Gold Souk - the worst thing is that its quite a run down area and the traffic to get back across the Creek is mind numbing.Ok so onto the Hotel itself. The hotel is quite small and a business hotel - not a place for families. The rooms are generously sized and the bathrooms nice black marble - very smart. All rooms face the Creek (ours did sort of) and there is a small roof top pool (see picture - warning get there early to find a space!!!) Lots of European business travallers staying at this hotel and the front desk team were capable of speaking many languages. So why isnt this a 5 star hotel? Well its the little things that stand 5 stars apart. For example no-one was available to hail you a taxi out the front of the hotel - or no-one was there to open the front door for you when you arrived with your shopping. Small things I know, but something you would expect at a top class hotel.Didnt eat at the Verre Restaurant (Dont like frogs legs - the menu didnt look as expensive as I thought it may have been) - although it was always busy of dinner. Room service was good and we ate in the Glasshouse restaurant that was ok as well.Finally I would like to mention the Hilton Jumerah Beach (The Creek's sister hotel) that we visited on the daliy bus trip. I have enclosed a picture of the magnitude of the building work in the marina which simply dwarfs the hotel. Despite the Marina being &quot;nearly completed&quot; the background hammering, welding and clanking would have driven me made if I stayed at this hotel more than a couple of hours longer - the same must go for the Oasis Beach which was next door or the magnificent looking Grosnevor Hotel that was just up the road. This is a personal thing - but you have been warned!!!!	
Dec 23 2006 	Nice Hotel but stay nearer the beach!	Stayed here in September for 3 nights on holiday. I not sure if this hotel was originally just and empty building which Hilton took on because although its stylish it definitely have a look of an office block. Because I am Gold Hilton member I was immediately upgraded to a nice room with floor to ceiling windows on two sides with a good view of the Creek. The down side of the upgrade we was that we was not allowed to use the Executive Lounge and to be honest it was so small and crowed we didn’t miss much. I wasn’t too happy on how I was told I wasn’t welcome in the lounge; the lady on the desk was quite abrupt and unpleasant when all she needed to do was to explain the situation in a professional and polite manner (0 out of 10 for customer service in the lounge). The pool on the roof is very pleasant with good views over the city, it has a small bar area and food can be ordered although; the shaded seating area is a little on the small side but the bar/pool attendant couldn’t do enough for you and always with a smile. We ate once at the Gordon Ramsey Restaurant - Le Vere which was superb and very reasonably priced much better value than the Al Mahara at the Burj Al Arab, we ate there as a celebration meal for our wedding anniversary and although the food was good it was very very expensive. In would definitely recommend Le Vere, even if you are not staying at the Hilton but book well in advance and make sure you leave plenty of time to arrive, the traffic between 5pm and 8pm in Dubai/Derail is absolutely horrendous. Don’t bother with the bar it has no life at all, this is primarily a business hotel and the bar was empty on every occasion we passed. The room service menu is good with a very efficient service. Breakfast is OK nothing special.The problem with this hotel is its location, Dubai city itself has not got a great deal to offer and if you venture to the Gold Souk beware that Taxi drivers are unwilling to take you back because its just a short distance (to far to walk though and imposable in the heat and humidity). The guidebooks tell you that the Taxi drivers are not allowed to refuse a fare but they keep the doors locked and ask were you are going before they let you in, then say they don’t understand English and drive off! We eventually got a taxi but the driver said he had no change so the fare was not what I expected to pay. Overall the Taxi fares are reasonable and they are definitely the best way to travel.One good experience we had at this hotel was because of my Gold status we got complementary transport to the airport on our departure in I a very nice car (10 out of 10 for customer service this time!)I would not 100% recommended this hotel if you are on holiday, it’s a good business hotel and I would stay again if on business in Dubai. The hotel runs a shuttle service to its sister hotel on Jeremiah beach which is 20-30 minutes away (could double during rush hour) my advice would be stay at the beach it has more to offer and travel in to Dubai City if you want to.	
Dec 21 2006 	Dubai's finest "city hotel"	Arriving in the heat of Summer, the Hilton Dubai Creek was a welcome respite. Our room was superb - very large for a standard room and the black marble bathrooms are very luxurious. The entire atmosphere of the hotel is unlike any other Hilton I have stayed at - it is like a boutique hotel. The staff service is excellent, and although it is quite tall, it is actually a fairly small hotel. The rooftop pool is just great. We stayed in a standard room, however some people we were with had a massive suite, I believe it was an executive club suite, and it was amazing. It had its own bar, cappucino machine, two bathrooms and enormous wrap-around balcony. Breakfast here is extremely good - a buffet of cold foods and a menu (my god, a breakfast MENU!) to order your substantial hot food which comes out looking like something from an extremely exclusive restaurant.Anyway, bottom line is: I cannot recommend this hotel highly enough. It's fantastic. Obviously it's a city hotel so it's not on the beach, but if you don't want to be in a resort then this is the hotel for you.	
Nov 20 2006 	LOVED IT!	Had eaten at Glasshouse a couple of times on previous visits and always liked the look of this hotel. So when my friend and I decided to come for a weekend shopping trip from Pakistan where we live at the moment, it was my first choice. We got a free pick up from the airport and the driver was waiting with my name on a board. We checked in at the Executive lounge and had tea and smoked salmon sandwiches whilst the receptionist went through the formalities. We had asked for a twin room which wasn't available on the Executive floor so we were given a room on a lower floor but still had access to the Executive lounge. The room was lovely, twin beds facing a wall of glass looking down the creek and out to sea in the distance. The bathroom was gorgeous - a big bath, huge separate shower, all in black and grey marble and granite and a complimentary rubber duck. Our room was very quiet and the beds were comfy so we got a good nights sleep following our mega-shopping trips! The location is good - City Centre mall is a short taxi ride away (walkable at a pinch) and M&amp;S, Toys R Us, Reef Mall, Al Ghurain mall and the gold souk are all pretty close as well. On all but one occasion we managed to get a taxi almost straight away outside the hotel, although the odd driver would refuse to take us when he realised we weren't going far - one pretended he didn't know where the gold souk was! The hotel also has a complimentary shuttle bus to a different shopping mall once each day. Breakfast was served in Glasshouse and was very good - hot dishes such as bacon and eggs, french toast, pancakes, eggs benedict etc are ordered a la carte and served directly to you. We had dinner in the Glasshouse one night and as ever it was excellent. The executive lounge serves tea, coffee, cold drinks and snacks all day and from 6 to 8pm has &quot;happy hour&quot; with wine, spirits and beer plus hot snacks, houmus, cheeses, etc. Only complaint is it is very small and gets busy at happy hour so you have to get there early to get a seat! Staff at the hotel were all very friendly and helpful and housekeeping replenish towels and toiletries in the evening when they do the turn down service. I really couldn't fault this hotel, it was a fab experience from the moment we were picked up at the airport to being dropped off there again 3 nights later.	
