Oct 21 2006 	Great location	We stayed here for a week during October and found it really difficult to fault the hotel. The staff, as is so often the case, are the greatest asset a hotel can have and the staff at the Dubai Creek Hilton were a cut above so many we have previously encountered. Within a couple of days we were being addressed by name, the staff at breakfast reserved a regular table for us and nothing was too much trouble. The accommodation was very good. we stayed on the thirteenth floor with marvellous views of the dhow wharf and the creek and were near enough to the roof top pool to walk up the stairs, where, although it is fairly compact there was always enough space and, although it was Ramadan, there was a screened area for the service of refreshments, most welcome in average day time temperatures of 36C.The room itself was large by any standards, with floor to ceiling windows and a large bathroom. The only gripe in this respect was that we had been sold the room as a triple. What this in fact meant was that a 'camp bed', was provided. Luckily the third member of our party is quite petite and managed OK, but it was effectively only suitable for a child or small adult . I suggest that if you intend to book a triple or quad room you check what exactly you are getting (we booked through BA holidays).Food in the hotel was really very good - we thoroughly enjoyed the breakfasts and when not out and about, either dined in the Glasshouse restaurant or had room service.The hotel organised a car and driver for us on most days and we did trips to Abu Dhabi and Al Ain (don't miss out on Jebel Hafeet if you do the latter) as well as being available for us most days for city tours and general running about. The cost was less than it would have been to go on organised trips with a tour company and I strongly recommend it rather than that or hiring a a car yourself.We recommend the Heritage village and the Dubai museum, as well as the regular Gold Souk, shopping mall, dinner on a boat on the creek and similar excursions. We did not go to Wild Wadi and so can't comment, neither did we go dune bashing, but both seemed to be great fun for the young and energetic (we are neither). We strongly recommend a visit to the Jumeirah mosque, where they have short (an hour or so) educational visits for non Muslims after which questions can be put, which were answered with honesty and diplomatically - some questions were a bit confrontational.The hotel also provided a shuttle service to the Hilton Jumeirah beach, which had a reasonable beach and provides facilities for changing and showering, as well as use of all the facilities. In addition there is a free shuttle service from the hotel to various locations in Dubai - a different location every day (this is not well advertised - you may need to ask).One last adverse criticism - the executive lounge is woefully small - only fourteen seats and three internet desk stools. On a number of occasions we couldn't get a seat for the happy hour free drinks and snacks and had to go elsewhere in the hotel and of course pay.All in all though it is a great hotel, not too big (140 rooms or so), in a central location, near the airport, great staff and much quieter than it's sister hotel in Jumeirah. I strongly recommend it.	
Oct 21 2006 	Very good but watch the sting in Ramsays	My wife and I took a five day break from work in Saudi Arabia in July. Our first stay at the Hilton and a very good hotel but we were not happy with Ramsays restaurant (see below) . We took one of the executive rooms on the upper floors. Modern decor, full height windows and a great bathroom. Good location with most places within a short taxi ride. Nice modern airy breakfast room and the exchange arangement with the Jumeirah Beach Hilton is worth using.. we had a good day on the beach there. Staff were possibly too attentive.. a number of calls from various members to check whether we were happy with the room/tidyness/etc etc. As to Ramsays.. very good menu, excellent food but SMALL (and I mean small) portions. I was astonished however at the blatant con trick pulled by the staff as my wife and I arrived for our meal. As we sat down the waiter said 'Glass of champagne sir' in such a manner that I (and my wife) assumed was some form of complimentary offer. It turned out that it wasn't.. the bill came to over 1000 Dh (about 150 pounds) and 460 Dh (about 60 pounds) of that was for the 2 glasses of champagne.Mr Ramsay should attend to that. Until he does we shall eat elsewhere when next in Dubai.	
Sep 17 2006 	We really enjoyed the Hilton Dubai Creek	Overall we really enjoyed our stay. We had booked into an Executive room, which included free airport transfers and access to the executive lounge.Our airport transfer was great, we took a while to get through passport control, but the driver/hotel contacted Emirates airlines to confirm that we indeed boarded in Glasgow. He basically waited for 2 hours! On route he was very chatty and offered us a cold drink of water. The check in went smoothly. When we arived in our bedroom there was rose petals on the bed and in the bathroom with a small oil burner lit. Everything was imaculate. The toiletries were from Crabtree and Evelyn and were heavenly. The staff were friendly and courteous throughout, although the accents can make it difficult for guests and staff to communicate properly.Breakfast was fabulous everyday and the fact that they serve breakfast to 11am everyday means you don't need to get up at the crack of dawn to eat. The selection was fabulous and the service was good.The rooftop pool was great, there was not many loungers (10 in all) and 3 tables. Considering this is more a business hotel, it seemed reasonable and we never struggled to get a lounger (although only went up twice). The pool I thought was a good size and great for a cool down and a few &quot;mini&quot; lengths. In previous reviews people stated that they were disappointed by the size of the pool, but i feel that if they wanted to do olympic laps they should go to an olympic swimming pool.The executive lounge was nice and peaceful during the day. I have to say that the staff member who was present in the lounge was not that &quot;hospitable&quot; in terms of checking whether we wanted anything and we had to get up to ask her for a refill of our soft drinks etc. The snacks at happy hour were nice and the one time we were in at happy hour the lounge wasn't too busy and although we do not drink alcohol, but noticed they had a wide selection.The small shop in the lobby had a great selection of curios/souveneirs, and some of the things were actually cheaper than Deira City Centre etc. So do have a look.Our room was right next to the executive lounge and we managed to connect to the wireless connection from the lounge in our room so basically had access 24/7 which was great.We did not actually dine in Verre or Glasshouse, but the menu for the Glasshouse looked nice and seemed reasonably priced.The only two negative points we experienced was the fact that the very fancy looking coffee machine did have any instructions on how to work it and when we did figure it out it only makes half a cup of coffee. We went without tea for 2 nights thinking we couldn't get any boiling water from the coffee machine and when the engineer came up he then pointed out that there was a kettle in the cupboard above the television (didn't even know it was a cupboard as it's all wood panelling and I wouldn't have reached it cos it's quite high up). We had asked for a non-smoking room, and for our whole stay (6 nights) this was fine, but we woke on the last day to the smell of smoke, sending me into a sneezing fit. Even when we got home and opened our suitcases our clothes still smelled of smoke. We did not say anything to the hotel (although in hindsight should've) as we were leaving the next day and it wasn't too much of a bother for us at that point as we were having such a great time in Dubai overall.We wouldn't pay this much for a hotel in Dubai again, as we really only used it as a base and feel that although we could afford it we'd rather spend our money on doing things in Dubai.	
